’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Crossebi was born in 1290, in Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Crossbi, was 21 and his mother, Maud de Kirkpatrick, was 20. He had at least 2 sons. He died in 1360, in his hometown, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1290–1360":"1290–1360","1339–Male":"1339–Surnud","1270–1314":"1270–1314","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1314":"1314","about 1314":"umbes 1314","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1339":"1339","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1290–1360":"1290–1360","1339–Male":"1339–Kuollut","1270–1314":"1270–1314","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1314":"1314","about 1314":"noin 1314","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1339":"1339","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1290–1360":"1290–1360","1339–Male":"1339–Décédé","1270–1314":"1270–1314","1270–Female":"1270–Décédée","1314":"1314","about 1314":"environ 1314","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1339":"1339","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Écosse","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Robert de Crossebi est né en 1290, à Écosse, Royaume-Uni, son père, Robert de Crossbi, avait 21 ans et sa mère, Maud de Kirkpatrick, avait 20 ans. Il a eu au moins 